# RevivifAI — Python project standards

Use **[Prek](https://prek.j178.dev/)** for pre-commit hook installation and management, **[Ruff](https://docs.astral.sh/ruff/)** for linting and formatting, and **[basedpyright](https://docs.basedpyright.com/)** for static analysis. Keep configuration consistent across dependency declarations and hook definitions.

## Dependencies

- **Required (dev):** **`prek`**, **`ruff`**, and **`basedpyright`**. Pin or bound versions deliberately so CI and local runs stay reproducible.
- Keep **`prek.toml`** hook **`rev`** values aligned with those packages (**`ruff-pre-commit`** ↔ **`ruff`**, **`basedpyright-prek-mirror`** ↔ **`basedpyright`**).

## `pyproject.toml` — Ruff

- Put **`[tool.ruff]`** (and nested tables) in **`pyproject.toml`** as the single source of truth. Run **`ruff check`** and **`ruff format`** locally or in CI using that config.
- The reference **`[tool.ruff]`** block below matches RevivifAI’s chosen rule sets and formatter options. Copy it into new projects, then set **`extend-exclude`**, **`[tool.ruff.lint.isort]`** **`known-first-party`**, and **`[tool.ruff.lint.per-file-ignores`** for each repository’s layout (package name, scripts/tests paths, generated or vendored trees).

### Reference `[tool.ruff]` configuration

```toml
[tool.ruff]
line-length = 120
target-version = "py312"
preview = true
extend-exclude = [
    "build",
    "dist",
    ".venv",
    ".mypy_cache",
    ".ruff_cache",
    # Add paths local to the repo (generated artifacts, caches, vendored trees).
]

[tool.ruff.lint]
# Professional rule selection. See: https://docs.astral.sh/ruff/rules/
#
# Unreachable-code note: PLW0101 (control-flow-graph-based unreachable detection)
# is implemented in Ruff's source but remains in an internal "testing" gate as of
# 0.15.11 and is not yet exposed via any public selector. Once it is promoted to
# preview/stable it will be activated automatically by ``preview = true`` +
# ``"PL"`` below — no config change will be needed.
select = [
    "E",      # pycodestyle errors
    "W",      # pycodestyle warnings
    "F",      # Pyflakes
    "I",      # isort
    "N",      # pep8-naming
    "UP",     # pyupgrade
    "B",      # flake8-bugbear
    "C4",     # flake8-comprehensions
    "SIM",    # flake8-simplify
    "TID",    # flake8-tidy-imports
    "PL",     # Pylint
    "RUF",    # Ruff-specific rules
    "PERF",   # Perflint
    "PIE",    # flake8-pie
    "RET",    # flake8-return
    "PTH",    # flake8-use-pathlib
    "ARG",    # flake8-unused-arguments
    "ERA",    # eradicate (commented-out code)
    "YTT",    # flake8-2020
    "ASYNC",  # flake8-async
    "FBT",    # flake8-boolean-trap
    "ICN",    # flake8-import-conventions
    "T20",    # flake8-print
    "ISC",    # flake8-implicit-str-concat
    "G",      # flake8-logging-format
    "Q",      # flake8-quotes
    "S",      # flake8-bandit (security)
    "D",      # pydocstyle
    "DOC",    # pydoclint (docstring ↔ signature consistency)
]
ignore = [
    "D100",    # Missing module docstring (internal modules don't need them everywhere)
    "D104",    # Missing package docstring in __init__
    "D105",    # Missing docstring in magic method
    "D107",    # Missing docstring in __init__
    "D203",    # Conflicts with D211 (no blank line before class)
    "D213",    # Conflicts with D212 (multi-line summary first line)
    "E501",    # Line length handled by the formatter
    "ISC001",  # Disabled to avoid conflict with the formatter
    "PLR0911", # Too many return statements (decision-heavy ML code)
    "PLR0913", # Too many arguments (common in ML configs)
    "PLR0912", # Too many branches
    "PLR0914", # Too many local variables (research scripts routinely exceed 15)
    "PLR0915", # Too many statements
    "PLR2004", # Magic value used in comparison (noisy for numeric ML code)
    "S101",    # Use of assert (fine in research/tests)
    "FBT001",  # Boolean positional arg (common in torch/HF APIs)
    "FBT002",  # Boolean default positional arg
    # ML / research-code idioms
    "G004",    # Logging f-strings: idiomatic and readable; lazy %-formatting is a micro-optimisation here
    "G003",    # Logging string concatenation: same rationale as G004
    "N803",    # Argument names follow linear-algebra conventions (X, W, Q, ...)
    "N806",    # Local variable names follow linear-algebra conventions (W, U, S, V, D, Q, ...)
    "N812",    # Conventional aliases (e.g. `import torch.nn.functional as F`)
]

[tool.ruff.lint.per-file-ignores]
# Examples only — add globs that match your CLI modules, scripts, and tests.
"tests/**/*.py" = ["S", "D", "PLR", "ARG"]
"**/__init__.py" = ["F401", "D"]

[tool.ruff.lint.isort]
known-first-party = ["your_package"]
combine-as-imports = true
split-on-trailing-comma = true

[tool.ruff.lint.pydocstyle]
convention = "google"

[tool.ruff.lint.flake8-tidy-imports]
ban-relative-imports = "all"

[tool.ruff.lint.pylint]
max-args = 10

[tool.ruff.format]
quote-style = "double"
indent-style = "space"
line-ending = "lf"
docstring-code-format = true
skip-magic-trailing-comma = false
```

## `pyproject.toml` — basedpyright

- **Mandatory:** declare **`[tool.basedpyright]`** next to **`[tool.ruff]`**. Set **`include`** (and **`exclude`** if needed) so all first-party Python under development is analyzed; set **`pythonVersion`** to match **`requires-python`** / **`[tool.ruff]`** **`target-version`**. Choose **`typeCheckingMode`** deliberately (**`standard`** or **`strict`** for typed codebases; document in config if you must start from **`off`** during a migration).
- Run **`basedpyright`** locally and in CI (same config as **`[tool.basedpyright]`**). Promote at least **`reportUnreachable = "error"`** unless a short-lived exception is documented in **`pyproject.toml`**.
- The hook in **`prek.toml`** must stay enabled so commits run the same analysis.

### Reference `[tool.basedpyright]` configuration

```toml
[tool.basedpyright]
include = ["src"]
# exclude = ["tests", "build", "dist"]
pythonVersion = "3.12"
typeCheckingMode = "standard"
reportUnreachable = "error"
```

Adjust **`include`** / **`exclude`** for your layout (src-layout, flat packages, generated stubs). Bump **`pythonVersion`** when the project’s baseline Python changes.

## `prek.toml`

- Keep a root **`prek.toml`** (Prek’s native config; see [Prek](https://prek.j178.dev/)). Match **`default_language_version.python`** to **`requires-python`** / **`[tool.ruff]`** **`target-version`**.
- The reference block below is the RevivifAI baseline: **`pre-commit-hooks`** hygiene, a **local** **`pygrep`** hook banning em dashes in Python, **Ruff** via **`ruff-pre-commit`**, and **basedpyright** via **`DetachHead/basedpyright-prek-mirror`**. **Do not remove** the **basedpyright** mirror block; adjust only **`rev`** when upgrading **`basedpyright`**. You may trim optional hygiene hooks if justified, but keep **`ruff-pre-commit`** and **basedpyright** **`rev`** values aligned with dev dependencies.

### Reference `prek.toml` configuration

```toml
minimum_prek_version = "0.3.9"
default_language_version.python = "3.12"
default_install_hook_types = ["pre-commit"]
default_stages = ["pre-commit"]
fail_fast = false

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# pre-commit/pre-commit-hooks
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
[[repos]]
repo = "https://github.com/pre-commit/pre-commit-hooks"
rev = "v6.0.0"

[[repos.hooks]]
id = "check-added-large-files"
args = ["--maxkb=20480"]

[[repos.hooks]]
id = "check-case-conflict"

[[repos.hooks]]
id = "check-merge-conflict"

[[repos.hooks]]
id = "check-toml"

[[repos.hooks]]
id = "check-yaml"

[[repos.hooks]]
id = "check-json"

[[repos.hooks]]
id = "check-executables-have-shebangs"

[[repos.hooks]]
id = "check-shebang-scripts-are-executable"

[[repos.hooks]]
id = "check-symlinks"

[[repos.hooks]]
id = "destroyed-symlinks"

[[repos.hooks]]
id = "detect-private-key"

[[repos.hooks]]
id = "end-of-file-fixer"

[[repos.hooks]]
id = "trailing-whitespace"
args = ["--markdown-linebreak-ext=md"]

[[repos.hooks]]
id = "mixed-line-ending"
args = ["--fix=lf"]

[[repos.hooks]]
id = "debug-statements"

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# local
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
[[repos]]
repo = "local"

[[repos.hooks]]
id = "no-em-dash"
name = "Forbid em dashes (U+2014) in Python source"
language = "pygrep"
entry = "—"
types = ["python"]

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# astral-sh/ruff-pre-commit
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
[[repos]]
repo = "https://github.com/astral-sh/ruff-pre-commit"
rev = "v0.15.11"

[[repos.hooks]]
id = "ruff-check"
args = ["--fix", "--exit-non-zero-on-fix"]
types_or = ["python", "pyi"]

[[repos.hooks]]
id = "ruff-format"
types_or = ["python", "pyi"]

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# DetachHead/basedpyright-prek-mirror
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
[[repos]]
repo = "https://github.com/DetachHead/basedpyright-prek-mirror"
rev = "1.39.2"

[[repos.hooks]]
id = "basedpyright"
pass_filenames = false
always_run = true
```

## Version alignment checklist

When bumping Ruff, Prek, or basedpyright:

1. Update dev dependency constraints (**`ruff`**, **`prek`**, **`basedpyright`**).
2. Update **`minimum_prek_version`** when adopting a newer Prek baseline.
3. Update **`pre-commit-hooks`** **`rev`** when bumping that bundle (follow upstream tags).
4. Update **`ruff-pre-commit`** **`rev`** to match the **`ruff`** release line you use.
5. Update **`basedpyright-prek-mirror`** **`rev`** to match the **`basedpyright`** version you depend on.
6. Re-run **`prek`** install/update so installed hooks match the repo config.

## Bootstrap

After cloning, contributors should install dev dependencies, run **`basedpyright`** (or rely on the Prek hook) against **`[tool.basedpyright]`**, and install hooks with Prek’s documented workflow so local commits match CI.
